04224nam a22007215i 9781400829682DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2010    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008296827 a10.1515/97814008296822doi  a(DE-B1597)501609  a(OCoLC)781295788  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDR557 7aHIS0100102bisacsh 7aHIS0260002bisacsh 7aHIS0370002bisacsh 7aHIS0370502bisacsh04a956.0151 aHanio?lu, M. ?ükrü, eauthor.12aA Brief History of the Late Ottoman Empire /cM. ?ükrü Hanio?lu. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4c©2008  a1 online resource :b17 halftones. 2 line illus. 8 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration, Place Names, and Dates -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Ottoman Empire at the Turn of the Nineteenth Century -- t2. Initial Ottoman Responses to the Challenge of Modernity -- t3. The Dawn of the Age of Reform -- t4. The Tanzimat Era -- t5. The Twilight of the Tanzimat and the Hamidian Regime -- t6. From Revolution to Imperial Collapse: The Longest Decade of the Late Ottoman Empire -- tConclusion -- tFurther Reading in Major European Languages -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aAt the turn of the nineteenth century, the Ottoman Empire straddled three continents and encompassed extraordinary ethnic and cultural diversity among the estimated thirty million people living within its borders. It was perhaps the most cosmopolitan state in the world--and possibly the most volatile. A Brief History of the Late Ottoman Empire now gives scholars and general readers a concise history of the late empire between 1789 and 1918, turbulent years marked by incredible social change. Moving past standard treatments of the subject, M. Sükrü Hanioglu emphasizes broad historical trends and processes more than single events. He examines the imperial struggle to centralize amid powerful opposition from local rulers, nationalist and other groups, and foreign powers. He looks closely at the socioeconomic changes this struggle wrought and addresses the Ottoman response to the challenges of modernity. Hanioglu shows how this history is not only essential to comprehending modern Turkey, but is integral to the histories of Europe and the world. He brings Ottoman society marvelously to life in all its facets--cultural, diplomatic, intellectual, literary, military, and political--and he mines imperial archives and other documents from the period to describe it as it actually was, not as it has been portrayed in postimperial nationalist narratives. A Brief History of the Late Ottoman Empire is a must-read for anyone seeking to understand the legacy left in this empire's ruins--a legacy the world still grapples with today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400829682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400829682.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN